Japan, Malaysia, Philippines, South Korea: Asian Bonds, Currency Preview

-- B y   K h a l i d   Q a y u m
-- 
2011-04-03T22:56:25Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-03/japan-malaysia-south-korea-philippines-asian-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in  Asia ’s bonds and currencies
today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the previous
trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan : Chief Cabinet Secretary Yukio Edano will hold media
briefing at 11 a.m. and 4 p.m. in  Tokyo .  The yield on the 1.3 percent government bond due March 2021
was at 1.28 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co., the
nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 84.20 per dollar at 7:44 a.m. in Tokyo.  Malaysia: Bank Negara will sell 3 billion ringgit ($992
million) of 210-day bills and 2 billion ringgit of 91-day
Islamic notes.  The yield on the benchmark 4.16 percent note due July 2021
was 4.11 percent. The ringgit was at 3.0255 per dollar.  South Korea : The Bank of  Korea  will release data on foreign
exchange reserves for March. Reserves stood at $297.7 billion in
the previous month.  The government will auction a combined 2.9 trillion won
($2.7 billion) of 91-day, 182-day and three-year bonds.  The yield on the government’s 3 percent note due December
2013 was 3.67 percent, according to prices from the Korea Stock
Exchange. The won was at 1,091.20.  Singapore: The government will sell S$3.9 billion ($3.1
billion) of 91-day bills.  The yield on the 3.25 percent bond due September 2020 was
2.49 percent. The Singapore dollar was at S$1.2624 per dollar.  Philippines: The government plans to sell a combined 5.5
billion pesos ($127 million) of 91- and 364-day bills.  The yield on the 6.25 percent debt due January 2014 was at
5.04 percent. The peso was at 43.375 per dollar.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Khalid Qayum in  Singapore  at 
 kqayum@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
